    {
        "content": "<p>Searching for the regex <code>\\{.* : Decidable.*\\}</code> in Mathlib I find only a small number of such lemmas and looking at our history it seems that a number of them arrived in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib3/pull/7291\">https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib3/pull/7291</a> but I see no discussion of why to follow the non-standard pattern there.</p>",
        "id": 526974603,
        "sender_full_name": "Oliver Nash",
        "timestamp": 1751541940
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I therefore have two questions:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Does anyone understand why <code>simp</code> fails to fire in the example I give above?</li>\n<li>Should we change these lemmas to take their decidability as typeclass arguments?</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 526974718,
        "sender_full_name": "Oliver Nash",
        "timestamp": 1751541983
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think <code>rw</code> can succeed because elaboration order for <code>rw [thm]</code> is</p>\n<ol>\n<li>start elaborating <code>thm</code></li>\n<li>find all matches in the target by unification</li>\n<li>... do the rewrite ...</li>\n<li>finish elaborating <code>thm</code> (that is, try to synthesize any pending instances, etc.)</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In this case, it's able to pick up the <code>Decidable</code> instance through unification. I'd expected <code>&lt;-</code> rewrites to fail.</p>\n<p><code>simp</code> has a different elaboration order, but I'm not sure why it fails.</p>",
        "id": 526976407,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1751542590
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, this is very helpful. Of course the next question might be how to make <code>simp</code> succeed but it may not matter much if <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/26662\">#26662</a> goes through.</p>",
        "id": 526976858,
        "sender_full_name": "Oliver Nash",
        "timestamp": 1751542773
    }
]